I’m hearing it’s a war on fupa’s lol

Here is my two cents.

Fupa stands for fatty upper pelvic area which is known for being a issue amongst women. This is a area that has been stubborn and difficult for most women to get rid of. Ladies let me give you some game.

Here are 2 main things that add to fupa but also you can control:
- consuming inflammatory foods/ highly processed meals
This can increase the fatty deposits and bloating.

- High stress levels
Being stressed can also cause more storing of fat.

You definitely can help decrease your fupa with watching what you are consuming and minimizing your intake of processed foods. Also, incorporating daily exercise to your routine which helps manage a caloric deficit and decrease stress.

Ladies I know it’s struggle, I’m just here to help.🙏🏽

This is the easiest way to calculate your calories for weight loss.

Understanding how many calories you should be eating to loss weight is the first step to setting you up for success.

This is the simplest formula to find out.

Formula below:

(Body weight) x 15 = maintenance calories

Maintenance calories are just another word for maintain the same weight.

(Maintenance calories) - 500 = deficit calories (weight loss)

3500 calories is the equivalent to 1lb.

If you eat 500 calories less than your maintenance calories for 7 days, you should lose about 1lb a week. (7 days x 500 calories = 3500 calories)

This is a start and a easy way to get things moving.

Hope this helps.

here are 4 vitamins you should use on the daily.

There are a lot of things we don’t get enough of in our diet and micronutrients (vitamins) are some of them.

The benefits of these vitamins:

calcium, magnesium, zinc: bone strength, mood, immunity, blood sugar regulation, and sleep quality.

omega 3’s: fight inflammation and may help prevent heart disease and a decline in brain function.

pre/probiotics: stimulates the growth of healthy bacteria in the gut.

multivitamin: fill nutritional gaps and make sure people get their daily allowance of underconsumed nutrients that are not received through nutrition.

try adding these to your daily routine.

The best practices to help you get shredded.

- Drink 1/2 your body weight in ounces of water daily.
 
Drinking water 100% calorie free, helps you burn more calories and can even help you suppress your appetite.

- Count your macros/ track your calories
The easiest way to know where you are is by knowing where you should be in comparison. You only know by tracking the numbers.

- Prioritize protein
High protein intake can’t help boost metabolism, keep you full, and help build lean muscle. 1g per lb of body weight is what you should aim for.

-Weight training
Lifting weight helps you build lean muscle and burn fat. It’s the best option thing if you are trying to keep muscle as you lean out.

These are the best things I find helpful. 🤝🏽

Stay Grinding

Tracking your food intake daily is a game-changer for fitness success. Here are 3 reasons why it’s a must-do:⠀
⠀
1️⃣ Accountability: Knowing exactly what you’re eating keeps you honest and helps you stay on track towards your fitness goals. No more guessing or mindless snacking.⠀
⠀
2️⃣ Portion control: Measuring your food helps you understand portion sizes and prevents overeating. It’s a powerful tool to maintain a healthy calorie balance and shed those extra pounds. 
⠀
3️⃣ Fine-tune your nutrition: By tracking your food intake, you gain valuable insights into your macronutrient and micronutrient consumption. This enables you to make informed choices, optimize your nutrition, and fuel your body for peak performance!

Counting your calories on your fitness journey is important for the following reasons: 

1. Caloric Balance: Counting calories allows you to achieve and maintain a caloric balance that aligns with your specific goals. Whether you aim to lose weight, gain muscle, or maintain your current physique, understanding your caloric intake is essential. By tracking calories, you can ensure you’re in the right energy balance to support your desired progress and optimize your results.

2. Precision and Adjustments: Counting calories provides a precise measurement of your daily energy consumption. This precision enables you to make informed adjustments to your diet based on your progress. If you’re not seeing the desired results, you can analyze your calorie intake and make necessary modifications. Additionally, accurately counting calories helps you avoid overeating or under-eating, both of which can hinder your progress.

3. Nutritional Awareness: Calorie counting promotes nutritional awareness by encouraging you to evaluate the quality of the foods you consume. It’s not just about the quantity but also the nutrient density of your meals. By tracking calories, you become more conscious of the macronutrient composition (protein, carbohydrates, fats) of your diet. This awareness helps you make healthier choices, ensuring that your body receives the necessary nutrients for optimal performance and recovery.

Counting calories empowers you to achieve a caloric balance, make precise adjustments, and cultivate nutritional awareness. These factors are crucial for monitoring and optimizing your progress and results on your fitness journey.

In other words. If you knew better, you’d do better.

Stay Grinding.

Stop skipping the most important meal.

Eating breakfast has several benefits. Here are three reasons why you should consider having breakfast:

1. Energy Boost: After a long overnight fast, your body needs energy to function optimally. A nutritious breakfast, rich in carbohydrates, protein, and fiber, can help replenish glycogen stores and provide a steady release of energy throughout the morning.

2. Improved Concentration and Focus: By providing your brain with essential nutrients, breakfast can improve concentration, memory, and attention span. This can be particularly beneficial for students, professionals, or anyone requiring mental clarity in the morning.

3. Weight Management: Eating a healthy breakfast can contribute to weight management. By starting your day with a balanced meal, you’re less likely to experience intense hunger later in the day, which can lead to overeating or unhealthy snacking. Breakfast can also kick-start your metabolism, aiding in calorie burning throughout the day.

Remember, everyone’s dietary needs and preferences are different, so it’s important to choose a breakfast that suits your individual goals and preferences.
